{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "We used the default calculation parameters provided by the source package for each fingerprint.Five categories of fingerprints were considered, based on the type of molecular information they capture:• Path-based fingerprints generate molecular features by analyzing the paths through the molecular graph given a pair of atoms and hashing them inside a fixed-size vector [16].",
    "For example, Depth First Search (DFS) represents a compound by storing all unique paths in its graph, obtained by using each atom as the path starting point and moving away up to a number of bonds d. [32] Another example of this [38,39].",
    "To do so, they initially represent each atom according to some properties, such as atomic mass or valence.",
    "Then, for each atom, the numerical identifier of neighboring atoms is added, thus generating a fragment identifier.",
    "This process can be repeated several times, progressively increasing the radius of the neighborhood to consider when aggregating information."
  ],
